  <chapter id="terminal">
    <title>The GNOME terminal users guide.</title>
    
    <sect1 id="Description">
      <title>Description</title>
      <para>
	gnome-terminal is a terminal emulator program that is part of the
	GNOME project.  It provides access to the Unix shell on the GNOME
	environment. </para>

      <para>
	gnome-terminal supports color display (see the section on
	environment variables for details) and provides mouse support
	to applications that are aware of mouse events for xterm-like
	terminals. </para>
    </sect1>
    
    <sect1 id="Emulation">
      <title>Emulation</title>
      <para>   The emulation supported by GNOME terminal is the same as
	the xterm program as provided by the X consortiums xterm program
	(which is in turn an almost complete emulation of the VT102 DEC
	terminal).</para>
      
      <para>The GNOME terminal supports the same extensions to the VT102
	that the xterms provide (trough special escape sequences, see the
	technical guide for the details).
      </para>
    </sect1>

    <sect1 id="config">
      <title>Configurable options</title>

      <sect2 id="colorschemes">
	<title>Color schemes</title> 

	<para>gnome-terminal supports three color schemes: the Linux
	  console scheme, the color Xterm scheme and the rxvt color
	  scheme.  These define the intensity and colors for the
	  sixteen ANSI color combinations that are supported by the
	  terminal.</para>
      </sect2>

      <sect2 id="colorcombos">
	<title>Primary color combination</title>

	<para>When no colors are specified, the program can use a
	  number of values for the default foreground and background
	  colors.  White and black in the following description map to
	  the colors as defined by the color scheme for white and
	  black. </para>
	
	<para>The stock supported modes are: white on black, black
	  on white, green on black and black on light yellow.</para>
      </sect2>

      <sect2 id="selcolor">
	<title>Setting the foreground and background</title>
	<para>In addition to the stock color combinations for
	  foreground and background the user can select its own
	  foreground and background colors from the property
	  box.</para> 
	
	<para>Additionally, the user can drag a color from any GNOME
	  color selector or color source and drop it into the
	  terminal.  If the user drops the color on a white space, it
	  will set the background, if the user drops the color on a
	  cell that contains a character, it will change the
	  foreground. </para>
      </sect2>
    </sect1>
    
    <sect1 id="classes">
      <title>Terminal classes</title>
      <para>The GNOME terminal allows you to have different configuration
	profiles to suit different uses.  To do this you only need to
	provide a name for your new configuration class by entering the
	new name in the property configuration dialog box.</para>
      
      <para>To activate a specific class at program startup you can use
	the --class command line option. </para>
    </sect1>
    
    <sect1 id="Options">
      <title>Command line options</title>
      <para>
	<itemizedlist>
	  <listitem>
	    <para><symbol>--background COLOR</symbol></para>
	    
	    <para>Used to specify the 
	      background color for the terminal at startup.  The COLOR can be
	      any form accepted by your windowing system.
	    </para>
	  </listitem>
	  
	  <listitem>
	    <para><symbol>--class CLASSNAME</symbol></para>
	    <para>
	      CLASSNAME Specifies the terminal class used to configure the
	      terminal at startup.
	    </para>
	  </listitem>
	  
	  <listitem>
	    <para><symbol>--command CMD, -e CMD</symbol></para>
	    <para>
	      Runs the CMD command at startup time
	    </para>
	  </listitem>
	  
	  <listitem>
	    <para><symbol>--font FONT</symbol></para>
	    <para>
	      Sets the font of the terminal to FONT
	    </para>
	  </listitem>
	  
	  <listitem>
	    <para><symbol>--foreground COLOR</symbol></para>
	    <para>
	      Sets the foreground of the terminal to COLOR.
	    </para>
	  </listitem>
	  
	  <listitem>
	    <para><symbol>--geometry GEOMETRY</symbol></para>
	    <para>
	      Specifies the startup geometry for this terminal.   The
	      geometry specifies the desired width and height in
	      terminal characters.  For example: --geometry=80x40 will
	      create an eighty column by fourty line terminal.</para>
	      <para>FIXME:  LInk to gnome-libs document on GEOMETRY specifications
	      when it is written
	    </para>
	  </listitem>
	  
	  <listitem>
	    <para><symbol>--login</symbol></para>
	    <para>
	      Make gnome-terminal launch the shell in login mode (it will run
	      all of your login initialization scripts in this mode). 
	    </para>
	  </listitem>
	  
	  <listitem>
	    <para><symbol>--nologin</symbol></para>
	    <para>
	      Make gnome-terminal only launch a shell.
	    </para>
	  </listitem>
	  
	  <listitem>
	    <para><symbol>--noutmp</symbol></para>
	    <para>
	      Indicates that this and the associated shell should not be
	      registered in the system database of users logged into the
	      computer. 
	    </para>
	  </listitem>
	  
	  <listitem>
	    <para><symbol>--utmp</symbol></para>
	    <para>
	      Indicates that the user wants this terminal to be
	      registered in the system database of users logged into
	      the computer (the utmp database).  This is the default.
	    </para>
	  </listitem>
	  
	  <listitem>
	    <para><symbol>--title TITLE, -t TITLE</symbol></para>
	    <para>
	      Makes GNOME terminal use TITLE for the window caption.
	    </para>
	  </listitem>
	</itemizedlist>
	
      </para>
    </sect1>
    
